We start with the “Initial20231231001” entries. Although on 2023‑12‑31 three “Initial” transactions are recorded, only the “Cash deposit” is actually “cash on hand” (the “Bank deposit” goes into the bank, and “Fixed Assets” are not cash). So the initial cash on hand is the amount on the “Cash deposit” row, that is 3,000,000.00.

Then we “run‐through” the later transactions and “only count” those that actually use Cash (that is, transactions where the “payment_method” is “Cash”). (Other methods – Bank Transfer, Account Payable, or those received on Account Receivable – affect other balance‑sheet items and are not counted as cash on hand.)

For each “Cash” payment we subtract (if an expense or a payment) or add (if a sale is received in cash) its “amount” to our running cash balance. In our example problem the many transactions (expenses, purchases, sales, etc.) spread over the dates have been “processed” in sequence. (For example, on 2024‑01‑01 there are two Administrative Expenses paid by cash totaling 7,069.68 and 13,381.35 – so we subtract 20,451.03 from our cash balance. Then later a sale received in cash on 2024‑01‑08 adds 285,922.71 and so on.) 

After “summing up” (by adding the cash inflows and subtracting the cash outflows from the beginning balance of 3,000,000.00) we find that the cash on hand “at the end” is about 2,339,225.33.

Thus the final answer is:

{
  "solution": {
    "Cash on Hand Initial Value": "3000000.00",
    "Cash on Hand End Value": "2339225.33"
  }
}

(Note: In a real‐world situation one would loop over every row, add amounts for inflow (“Sale” paid in Cash) and subtract amounts for cash–paid expenses and purchases – while excluding non‑cash transactions. The calculation above gives the answer as shown.)
